Hi, welcome to your confessional channel! This is a place for you to dump all of your thoughts about the game, just like confessionals on the actual show! Throughout the game, you will also receive questions about things going on in the game in this channel. These can either be from a member of production, or from a spectator. (If it is a question from a spectator, it will need to be pre-approved by production before you can see it.) We encourage you to share as many of your thoughts on anything and anyone in the game as youre comfortable with! This is a place for people to see a log of your journey from day 1 to final tribal council. Right now, the only people who have access to viewing your confessionals are members of Production, and our Super Spectators! Super Spectators are all vetted & trusted individuals in the community, so you dont have to worry about any leaks. If you want to make sure ONLY members of production can see a message, you should use your submissions channel instead. That channel will also be used for challenge submissions. Congrats once again on being casted! For now, feel free to give the specs a quick intro! Where are you from, how old are you, what are you into?

22:39
2. Align with good players, not bad players So, I had a few fairly close relationships with smorgon. And looking at them tribe by tribe, my relationships with what ended up being the final 3 ended up being the most helpful to my game. By being close / appearing close with the people at the top of trust rankings, I was protected. Had I adopted a similar strategy on the tribe when I was voted out, I would have had a decent shot at making merge. Instead, I ended up being associated with someone who's game was long sunk, (sorry but it's true lol), causing me to get out, among other factors. My goal is to be the 1 on the trust rankings of the person who is topping trust rankings (edited)
22:43
3. Pay close attention to what people actually want This one's a tricky one. Last time I played, my goal was to align with people who's best move was to work with me. It worked it until it didn't. Thinking about my highest odds chance of surviving that tribe, it was actually working with someone who would have been very actively mispalying by trusting me. Because I knew that her trusting me would be a mistake, I ignored the possibibilty of working with her, and instead chose to try and work with people who i felt would be making a mistake in voting me out (but didn't actually want to work with me). In short, a lot of times people will convince themselves that working with the person they like is a good strategic decision when it isn't, and that voting out people they don't like is a good decision when it isn't. So I need to focus on aligning with the people who want to work with me, regardless of whether or not I feel it's a good idea for them
22:44
4. Let other people drive the boat As a bit of a control freak, this one is more of a personal demon. I think ultimately, if I just be chill, talk to people, and don't really start stuff, I can at least make merge. Sometimes you gotta delegate, not every battle is worth fighting.

Pilot 08/31/2023 2:35 AM
Closing Thoughts: Alright so before I accept my money, I just wanna wrap up my thoughts here about what I feel I did right and what I feel I did wrong, and what I will do if/when I compete in one of these bad boys again. At the start of this game, I gave myself a few rules and pieces of advice based on my 1st ORG, so while it's still semi-fresh, let's write down what I learned here.
02:39
1. Making sure you MAINTAIN social connections. This is something I noticed in my last ORG too, but due to my early departure, it didn't really get to sink in. The biggest force in my way of winning this game was Paris, no doubt about it (sorry Max). Part of that was that I let her get really close to other people. I had the good fortune of swapping with her twice in a row. And she was my number 1 ally the entire time, had I worked on maintaining that SOCIAL connection into the merge, this could have gone a lot easier, but I let her slip, we stopped doing as much fun stuff and having as many fun conversations and that encouraged her to leave my side. I've got to make sure that I stay someone people wanna talk to. I think I managed to make good first impressions, but in Smorgon I noticed that I dropped on people's trust rankings every cycle. Similar things were happening here too, where I can have good first day conversations, but I am having trouble transitioning that into a lasting bond. Which leads into my next point...
02:42
2. Show more personality. In an effort to make myself an appealing ally, I restricted a lot of my personality when actually interacting with people in this game. The version of me that players interacted with in this game was a kind of watered down version of my personality. I wanted to keep people from seeing me get mad, or sad, or afraid, or my annoying side, but it's hard to only restrict certain sides of your personality. The result was that I appear to have come across as a fairly bland person, which worked in my favor well enough, but even still I think I need to work harder on learning how to endear myself to people. I'll have to look back at the strategies some of the stronger social players from this season used and update my ORG personality accordingly.
Pilot 08/31/2023 2:50 AM
3. Don't brag so much about your strategic game in your FTC. My speech has gotten more than a little bit of flack. Entering FTC, I was predicting a 7-2 victory, I let it get far closer than that. This was largely due to the fact that I came across as arrogant. Now, even after reading my speech, it's clear that some of the jurors don't really understand my game, so on top of the arrogance, that just means it was poorly written. I did things like point out the jurors mistakes to them as justification of why I voted them, but I recognize how that could be seen as talking down to them. I had A LOT of control this game, the more I look back, the more I really grasp it, there are votes I wanted that I didn't even realize I had the power to push. Some jurors understood that, and some jurors didn't, either way, the kicker is that the way I went about speaking that truth made people not want to vote for me. Even if they did internalize the strengths of my game, the thing I have been saying all along as being Paris's strength in an FTC situation, was very nearly my down fall. Jurors will vote for who they want to win, it's so simple, but people forget it all the time. I entered that FTC as the person people were "supposed" to vote for, if I was the underdog, bragging about myself strategically might have worked, but the jury already knew they were "supposed" to vote for, even if they didn't grasp the full extent of it. I should have focused more on getting them to actually want to vote for me. This leads back into showing more personality, making more jokes, and just kind of allowing people to see a personable side of me that they'd, well, just want to hang out with or something.
02:53
4. Find out what about me in ORGs unnerves people. Ghost, Max, Cyril, Quack, Cwis, Muski, Joey Olberding. Something about me has consistently put people off to me and made them more hesistant to trust me in ORGs, regardless of whether or not they actually should. It's too much of a trend and too specific to me to not notice. I've seen too many "Pilot is untrustworthy but I can't really place why" comments over the course of the 2 ORGs I have played. This one is going to be tough to solve because I don't really know what's causing it, but I'm going to look into it.
02:58
5. Don't get complacent. This loops around back to the first one. I would set myself up well with someone, and I would assume that I would just be good with them for longer than I actually would be. I didn't really face consequences for this, but I think I started out setting myself up well with Aleksi, and I just assumed that I would stay someone he would trust, despite not really giving him much reason to down the line. At final 7 was the vote I paid least attention to, and shocker shocker, it's the one time I was out of the loop. FTC was another thing I felt I had on lock, and I almost messed it up. The same could kind of be said about final 4, but that really is a unique situation. Either way, gotta make sure I don't get overly complacent
03:02
6. Be less controlling. This one is a tough one for me. Just like in smorgon, I got called out for being a controlling my way or the highway type of player. I made a conscious effort to be less controlling, but there were times I still were. I definitely was able to make sure that I was having conversations rather than bossing people around, and I know that helped, but I still think there were a few too many times I asked people to say or do a certain thing without giving enough of an explanation. Or, I didn't trust my ally enough and tried to micromanage their actions to a degree they didn't like. I think this controlling side was really the main way my paranoia actually bled through from my confessionals. I would try and make sure ever person I was aligned with behaved exactly right, but honestly, in those low pressure situations, letting my allies make those little mistakes can be less harmful then trying to micromanage them, making them resent our relationship.
03:03
And that's all I got folks, I could talk about stuff I did well, but I'll keep that in my own personal notes for now. I'm probably gonna exit interview myself at one point LOL, so if I do end up doing and recording that maybe I'll post it.
03:04
Other than that, I think that's all I have to say, later peoples!
